    <p>While it's pretty hard to go wrong here, my recommendations are either a Steak Lupe for yourself, or the big Fajita platter for 2+. <br>The Steak Lupe is an absolute behemoth of a meal, featuring a huge slab of lime pepper marinaded steak covered with melted Monterey Jack cheese and pico de gallo. It comes with tortillas, beans, and rice to make your own burritos, but honestly I usually just clean the plate. </p>
    <p>The fajita is served on a sizzling hot platter, and continues to cook for a few minutes after they deliver it to your table. The smell is absolutely intoxicating....I'm getting hungry just thinking about it. It comes with all the fixin's - pico de gallo, guacamole, sour cream, shredded cheese, beans, rice, and some unbelievably soft tortillas. Don't order this unless you're okay with eating an absolutely barbaric amount of food, as the portion sizes are quite huge. You can choose your proteins as well - for my money the steak is the best bet, but the shrimp and chicken are not too shabby either.</p>
    <p>If those two sound a little bit heavy for you...come back when you're hungrier. They're absolutely the stars of the menu. But for other recommendations: the enchiladas are all delicious, and they have some surprisingly decent seafood too (no idea why, but it's there if you want it).</p>
    <div class="modal"></div>

    <h1>Final Thoughts</h1>
    <p>I realize I'm probably being a little bit hyperbolic, and definitely a lot biased. My parents live about 10 minutes from the original Lupe Tortilla, so it's no surprise that I ended up eating there a lot. There are some other pretty good Tex-Mex restaurants in Houston: Ninfa's comes to mind, as does El Tiempo and Escalante's. But if someone were to visit Houston, Lupe is where I would take them first. After many, many, <i>many</i> visits over the years, they have yet to let me down, and damnit I'll keep giving them my business until they do. </p>
